text: Monday's Supreme Court ruling on hobby
lobby and religious freedom was just one
front in the ongoing battle against the
Affordable Care Act how the 5-4 decision
fits amid the other legal challenges on
the New York Times minute since
president obama signed the bill into law
opponents have been challenging its
legality the most prominent challenge
was defeated in 2012 when the court
upheld the individual mandate this
week's decision represents a defeat for
the White House the Hobby Lobby craft
store chain as well as any other family
owned corporation can now cite religious
belief to deny the contraception
coverage that the law requires it could
scale back the reach of President
Obama's signature law and is likely to
set up new clashes over religious
freedom but will it represent the end of
the legal wrangling hardly watch for two
other challenges that could if
successful have even deeper implications
every last provision of Obamacare all
came from the Senate one challenge cites
the Constitution's origination clause
and arguing that the law was introduced
in the wrong house of Congress another
defeat here could lead to full repeal
another case questions federal
government subsidies within states that
have refused to set up their own
insurance exchanges that argument if
successful could deeply limit the number
of Americans able to sign up and those
are just two of the higher profile
challenges while both have a ways to go
before they would appear on the Supreme
Court docket these challenges ensure
that Monday's defeat for the law won't
be the end of the legal arguments over
President Obama's signature legislation
